    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-09-18T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-09-18T02:00:00-05:00" n="447"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d447">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/395: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Yugoslavia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Lane</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Belgrade</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-09-18T08:00:00+01:00"
                            >September 18, 1939—8 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 9:20 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>277. The Minister for Foreign Affairs<note n="59" xml:id="d447fn59">Aleksander
                        Cincar-Markovlch.</note> stated to me this evening that the invasion of
                    Poland by Soviet troops in no way alters Yugoslavia’s position. Although
                    admitting that the Soviet word is of doubtful value he considers that the Soviet
                    guarantee respecting Rumanian territory is helpful. He said he is more than ever
                    convinced that Italy will remain neutral and that Hungary will follow Italy’s
                    lead. He said that the Yugoslav Government is awaiting with much interest the
                    result of the visit to Moscow of the Turkish Foreign Minister<note n="60"
                        xml:id="d447fn60">Sukru Saracoglu.</note>
                    <pb facs="0449" n="437" xml:id="pg_437"/> particularly in view of Turkey’s
                    arrangements with France and Great Britain.</p>
                <p>The Minister of War<note n="61" xml:id="d447fn61">Gen. Milutin Neditch.</note>
                    informed me today that Rumania will undoubtedly accede to German demands for oil
                    and agricultural products.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lane</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
